Working on cyberdeck projects involves various safety hazards. Understanding and following safety practices protects you and your equipment.

## Electrical Safety

### Battery Safety
- Never short-circuit lithium batteries
- Always use proper protection circuits
- Charge batteries on non-flammable surfaces
- Never leave charging batteries unattended
- Store damaged batteries in safe containers

### High Voltage Warning
Some components can retain dangerous charges:
- Capacitors in CRT displays can hold lethal charges
- Always discharge capacitors before working on power circuits
- If unsure, assume any component is dangerous

### Power Supply Safety
- Use properly rated power supplies
- Check for recalls on PSU models
- Never bypass safety ground connections
- Ensure adequate ventilation for power components

## Soldering Safety

### Fume Exposure
Soldering produces potentially harmful fumes:
- Work in well-ventilated areas
- Use fume extractors or fans
- Lead-free solder reduces some hazards
- Wash hands after handling solder

### Burns Prevention
- Let equipment cool before working on it
- Use proper stands for hot irons
- Be aware of component leads that retain heat

## Tool Safety

### Eye Protection
- Always wear safety glasses when cutting, drilling, or soldering
- Flying debris can damage eyes permanently
- Include safety glasses in your toolkit

### Respiratory Protection
- Wear respirators when sanding or spray painting
- Use dust collection when possible
- Be aware of material safety data sheets (MSDS)

### Tool Operation
- Follow manufacturer guidelines for power tools
- Use sharp blades—dull tools require more force and are dangerous
- Secure workpieces properly before machining

## Fire Safety

### Hot Work
- Keep fire extinguishers accessible
- Have a fire blanket for small fires
- Never leave heat sources unattended
- Keep flammable materials away from hot work areas

### Electrical Fires
- Never use water on electrical fires
- Know how to use a CO2 or dry chemical extinguisher
- Disconnect power before attempting to fight electrical fires

## First Aid

Keep a basic first aid kit that includes:
- Burns treatment
- Eye wash solution
- Bandages and gauze
- Tweezers for splinters

Know the location of emergency services.
